                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.04418/93a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-28T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 28, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>507. From time to time suggestions have been made by persons in responsible
                    positions, including members of Congress, with respect to permanent neutrality
                    legislation. Among such suggestions are the following: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Embargo on all export trade to belligerents.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Embargo on the export of all war materials such as oil, steel, iron
                            and copper.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Embargo on all articles in the last mentioned category in excess of
                            the normal volume of shipments.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Any comment you may possibly care to make regarding the desirability or effect of
                    the enactment of any of these three proposals would be welcomed.</p>
                <p>Please send copy to Embassies at London, Rome and Berlin and Legation at
                    Bern.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carr</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
